After the free international order
Many analysts, including those at Cambridge, believe that the free international order came to an end with China's rise and the election of US President Donald Trump.
But if Joe Biden defeats Trump in the November election, should he strive to revive it?
Perhaps the outcome will not be like that, but he must find some alternative.
Critics point out that the US order after 1945 was neither always global nor always very free, which is correct.
It excludes more than half of the world (including the Soviet bloc and China) and includes many authoritarian countries.
American hegemony is always exaggerated.
Despite this, the strongest countries must lead in creating global public goods, otherwise they will not be provided – and Americans will suffer as a result.
The current pandemic is a good example.
A realistic goal of the Biden administration should be to establish an international system based on rules, with different member states participating in different matters.
Will China and Russia be willing to participate?
In the 1990s and 2000s, neither country was able to balance the power of the United States, which stood above sovereignty in its pursuit of liberal values.
The United States bombed Serbia without the approval of the UN Security Council and invaded Iraq.
It also supported a UN General Assembly resolution in 2005 on "responsibility to protect," aimed at providing protection to citizens brutally treated by their own governments — a principle that the US later used in 2011 to justify bombing Libya to protect civilians in Benghazi.
Critics describe this record as hubris among post-Cold War Americans — for example, when NATO's intervention in Libya ultimately led to regime change, Russia and China felt betrayed — while defenders of the action describe it as a natural evolution of international humanitarian law.
However, the growth of Chinese and Russian power has more strictly limited the scope for liberal interventionism.
So what's left?
Russia and China emphasize the principle of sovereignty as enshrined in the UN Charter, which holds that states can only go to war in self-defense or with the approval of the UN Security Council.
Since 1945, the use of force to occupy neighboring territories has been rare, and when it has happened, it has come at a high cost in the form of sanctions (as with Russia's annexation of Crimea in 2014).
Furthermore, the Security Council has frequently authorized the deployment of peacekeeping forces in countries in distress, and political cooperation has successfully limited the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and ballistic missiles.
This dimension of a rule-based order remains crucial.
Specifically, in terms of economic relations, the world needs to revise the rules.
Even before the pandemic, China's hybrid state capitalism supported an unfair mercantilist model, which distorted the functions of the World Trade Organization.
This will lead to the decoupling of global supply chains, especially when national security is under threat.
Although China complains that the US is blocking companies like Huawei from building 5G communication networks in the West, the US stance is consistent with the principle of sovereignty.
After all, China has blocked the operations of Google, Facebook, and Twitter in China for security reasons.
Negotiating new trade rules will help prevent decoupling escalation.
At the same time, despite the current crisis, cooperation in key financial areas remains very strong.
On the other hand, interdependence in the ecological field poses an insurmountable barrier to sovereignty, because threats transcend national borders.
Regardless of the setbacks to economic globalization, environmental globalization will continue, as it is governed by biological and physical laws, and contemporary geopolitical logic has no effect on it.
The issues mentioned above threaten everyone, but no country has the ability to solve the problems independently.
Power also has a so-called positive and constructive dimension in issues like the 2019 COVID-19 pandemic and climate change.
Under such circumstances, simply thinking about exercising power over others is not enough.
We must also think from the dimension of exercising power jointly with other countries.
The Paris Climate Agreement and the World Health Organization have helped us and others.
Since Nixon and Mao met in 1972, despite ideological differences, it has not affected cooperation between China and the US.
Biden faces the challenge of whether the US and China can cooperate in producing global public goods while engaging in competition in the traditional great power rivalry domain.
The digital space is a new and important issue — because it is partially transnational but also controlled by sovereign governments.
The internet has been partially fragmented.
Internet freedom and privacy rules can be established within democratic countries, but these rules will not be recognized by authoritarian countries.
As suggested by the Global Network Security Council, if authoritarian regimes also want to achieve interconnectivity, some rules prohibiting the alteration of the internet's fundamental structure are also in their interests.
However, when they use proxies to launch information warfare or intervene in elections (which infringe on sovereignty), they must strengthen norms through rules such as those negotiated by the United States and the Soviet Union during the Cold War, such as limiting escalation of naval events (although ideological hostility still exists).
The United States and like-minded countries must publicly declare the norms they intend to uphold and establish the necessary deterrence.
Upholding the values of a free internet space does not mean the United States will unilaterally disarm.
Rather, the United States should differentiate between allowable public soft power and secret information warfare, and retaliate when the other side launches secret information warfare.
It is allowed for Russia and China to broadcast programs and broadcasts openly, but manipulating social media and other secret unified actions are not allowed.
And the US will continue to criticize the human rights records of these countries.
Surveys show that the American public wants to avoid military intervention, but does not want to withdraw from alliances or multilateral cooperation.
And the public still values values.
If Biden is elected, the problem he faces is not whether to restore the free international order.
The issue is whether the US can cooperate with core allies to promote democracy and human rights, while also cooperating with a broader range of countries to manage transnational threats such as climate change, pandemics, cyber attacks, terrorism, and economic instability through a rules-based international system.
